{{A Beginner's Guide to D}}

D is a language following in the footsteps of the C-language family. It has the same general syntax, so anyone familiar with C, C++, Java or C# should be able to easily pick up the language. You should see the [http://www.digitalmars.com/d/comparison.html language comparison] page for more details.

Since this page is about a short introduction to D, why not start with the all-famous [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hello_world Hello World].

<source lang="D">
import std.stdio;

void main()
{
  writefln("Hello World!");
}
</source>
For the experienced C programmer, the import and writefln should look strange. We will discuss them in later chapters.

{{A Beginner's Guide to D}}

There is currently no finalized IDE tool ala [http://www.eclipse.org Eclipse] for D development. [http://www.vim.org Vim] and [http://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/ Emacs] come bundled with D editing modes, and since D is syntactically very similar to the other C-style languages, any editor which supports those might rudimentally support D.

However, for an exhaustive list of D-supporting IDEs, [http://www.prowiki.org/wiki4d/wiki.cgi?EditorSupport please refer here].

