{{MMM}}
[[Image:DVPMheader.png|Digital Video Production Manual]]
[[Movie Making Manual/Digital Video/Contents|Previous | Contents]]
==Introduction== This book is intended as a compendium to the Movie Making Manual, or a ‘Volume 2’ which addresses the specific needs and concerns of Digital Video Production in contrast to using film as a recording medium. Digital Video uses the common abbreviation of DV, and this book will use DV and DVP (Digital Video Production) frequently. Many of the concepts and techniques used for creating moving images using film is the same or similar as when using DV, however many tools and techniques used for each medium are specific to that application. This book concentrates specifically on video production techniques concentrating on digital video rather than analog since analog is all but an obsolete technology. This book also assumes the reader is at least somewhat proficient with the basic terminology of video production and computer use so not every little thing will be spelled out, however there is an appendix with abbreviations, definitions, and terms to assist as much as possible.
[[Movie Making Manual/Digital Video/History|Next | History of Video]]
{{BookCat}}

{{center|This category contains books on '''[[Subject:Computer science|computer science]]''': the study of the theoretical foundations of information and computation, and of practical techniques for their implementation and application in computer systems. It is frequently described as the systematic study of algorithmic processes that describe and transform information to answer the fundamental question underlying computer science: "What can be (efficiently) automated?".}} {{CategoryTOC}}
[[Category:Computing| {{SUBPAGENAME}}]]
[[eo:Kategorio:Udk:004]] [[es:Categoría:Informática]] [[fr:Catégorie:Informatique]] [[is:Flokkur:Tölvunarfræði]] [[nl:Categorie:Informatica]] [[pl:Kategoria:Informatyka]] [[vi:Thể loại:Khoa học máy tính]]

The Control Unit provides the Micro-Instructions that are necessary for the execution of a program. The micro instruction that should be executed next is decided based on the Current instruction fetched from memory and the bit values off the Various CPU status registers such as Negative, Zero etc.
Of the two CPU architectures in use the RISC (Reduced Instruction Set Computing) and the CISC (Complex Instruction Set Computing) have different philosophies in this regard where the RISC believes in having a larger number of more simple Micro-instructions and the CISC believes in a smaller number of more complex instructions.
== further reading == {{wikipedia|control unit}}
* [[Digital Circuits/Finite State Machines]] describes low-level detail of state machines in general, which includes control units. * [[Microprocessor Design]] describes some very complicated control units, and how to design your own.
